P.S. All sarcasm aside, it's worth noting that the reason that all the
Guardians were originally male is simply this: sexism was entrenched
and largely unquestioned in the 1950's/1960's, when they were
introduced. Plain and simple.

The Guardians were scientifically advanced, serious authority figures
undertaking a great task. Of COURSE they were all men. What would a
female Guardian do - take notes? Bring coffee?

Okay, that's a little sarcastic, but I'm not kidding. Remember that
when Wonder Woman joined the JSA - as their only female member - she
was their &quot;secretary.&quot;

A female Guardian (much less many female Guardians) would just have
looked out of place to the people of the time. Take a look at any shot
of the Krypton Science Council from the same era: all men.

Well, that was then. But the problem is, in a serial medium like
superhero comics, the unquestioned sexism of that era can be
perpetuated, not just by people who are actively sexist themselves,
but by anybody who just doesn't think about the question. You just
keep drawing the Guardians the way they used to be joined, and the
assumption that they are all male - with all its implications and
messages about the place of women - gets copied over into today's
comics.

Does that mean that you should suddenly make half the Guardians
female? Not necessarily. (Although it's worth noting that the author
who did that made it part of a storyline, based on a character's
decision. It wasn't just a proclamation or a retcon.)

But it does mean that people should question the inherited judgements
and assumptions of past eras, and make sure that they're not
recreating sexism or other prejudices where it's not necessary to do
so. Have a little sensitivity. Most of our grandparents were sexists,
simply because of the times they lived in; we don't have to blame them
for it, but we don't have to continue it either.

I don't really care whether half the Guardians were recreated female
or not. (And I think that the decision to bring them back as BABIES
was wrong, wrong, wrong!) But I do think that, in the recent
retconning of the Zamorans and the Star Sapphires, DC screwed up a
very big opportunity to replace the sexism of the past with something
a little more nuanced.

I mean, look at the new Star Sapphires: they entice Green Lanterns
into mating with them, kill them, and smother their planets into
stasis. It's hard to imagine a more concentrated dose of misogynistic
stereotypes: the black widow, vagina dentata, the &quot;smothering&quot; female
who takes away all freedom. (Why, it's Dave Sims' dream date!) Is
there no way they could have put some intelligence and decency into
these &quot;female Green Lanterns&quot; and &quot;female Guardians&quot;? Admittedly, even
the Oan Guardians are no great prize these days - but over the years
we've seen them as good, well-intentioned, and doing important things
to save the universe, as WELL as kind of dumb (just for Idiot Plot
purposes) and passive. The Zamarons have never even had a chance.
</POST>
