You're not wrong, but it wasn't inevitable.  Doc Smith's prototype for the
Oans, the Arisians, were often thought of as male by humans who interacted
with them, but in fact they were never seen, and the occasional woman who
got to Arisia sometimes perceived them as female.  Their successors, the
Children of the Lens, were in fact mostly female.

James Schmitz, another writer of the period, wrote mostly stories with
powerful and dynamic female protagonists, notably Telzey Amberdon, Trigger
Argee, and the witches of Karres.

My point being that the all-male nature of the Guardians really was
optional.
