Well, without reading what others have said so far...

The result, I think, is more of an &quot;everything we've told you is a LIE!&quot;
situation. It *finally* resolves the deal with the non-Carol Secret
Society of Super-Villains Star Sapphire in a fairly tidy fashion, with
the relationship at the end of Millennium being the only casualty I can
think of ... and you *might* be able to shoehorn that in somehow, though
I'm not altogether keen on doing so (especially the &quot;incompatible
symbiotes&quot; bit).

With that in mind, here's what I see as being the &quot;true&quot; history of the
Zamarons. They were a group of Oans who disagreed with the Guardians,
and presumably their brethren the Controllers, about how to deal with
the whole Krona thing (although the &quot;origin of Parallax&quot; at the end of
Countdown #35 this week implies that they may have been at the game for
more reasons than that). Presumably the Controllers wanted to take an
active, almost dictatorial, role in things. The Guardians chose logic.
The Zamarons chose emotions, presumably in spite of the Parallax entity.
They left, looking for inspiration and a focus for their power, and
found it in mysterious purple crystals that had consumed what they
presumed were two lovers joined forever in death. The purple crystals
had the ability to focus some form of emotional energy, much like the
Guardians' rings, though with some form of possession involved. The
&quot;Sapphires&quot; became their power ring equivalents, although their sole
purpose was to spread &quot;eternal love&quot; through them; the Sapphires would
possess a female that was attracted to a planet's Green Lantern, bond
with him, and thereby consume him; the crystal would then spread
throughout the planet, entombing them in love.

When they went after Earth's GL (Hal Jordan), they had to play down some
of the aspects of all this, as perhaps they did everywhere they went.
They created the fiction of wanting a queen, and Carol Ferris just
happened to resemble their last queen. Their purpose was to entomb &quot;in
love&quot; Earth, striking back at their own spurned lovers, the Guardians,
in the process.

Like I said earlier, the Millennium storyline is probably the most
vulnerable to the new status quo. Even then, though, it could work.
Perhaps the whole &quot;incompatible symbiote&quot; thing was yet another fiction,
or perhaps there was some truth there that both groups chose to ignore
initially. Perhaps the Zamarons that went with the original Guardians
were actually the female Guardians themselves, or perhaps the Guardians
that returned, except perhaps for Ganthet, were actually the offspring
of those ... heck, maybe these new Zamarons were, too. Or maybe it's
just not worth trying to shoehorn in Millennium after all, since it
eventually became a non-event except for Gloss, Jet, and Ram (although
their presence, and death in the latter case, really isn't worth keeping
all the baggage around anyhow).
