But don't you see that this is EXACTLY the same issue as Vulcans
having five fingers and voice boxes? If you are going to have human
actors play Vulcans, you either have to (a) exclude all non-white
actors from the casting process, or (b) wind up with Vulcans that
appear to have the same spread of &quot;races&quot; as human beings. And why
would anyone in their right mind WANT to do (a)?

It's exactly the same artisitic license that produces human-looking
aliens in general.

I mean, look at this: Vulcan women wear their hair longer than Vulcan
men!  Isn't that an even worse &quot;obtrusive coincidence,&quot; in which the
styles common to modern-day U.S. culture not only extended to Star
Trek-future human culture, but to Star Trek-future Vulcan culture as
well! (And you could &quot;fix&quot; it without limiting your casting - just
have the actors cut their hair differently.)

Were you outraged the first time you saw a Vulcan female, and saw that
she had long hair? Didn't it seem far to coincidental to make sense?
If not, why not?

(Maybe you thought &quot;Since most cultures on Earth have two sexes, with
the women wearing their hair longer than the men, I think it's
reasonable to assume that's the most evolutionarily stable state, so
most aliens have two sexes, with the women wearing their hair longer
than the men.&quot;)

Most of the &quot;alien cultures&quot; portrayed in Star Trek have traits that
make them look very much like contemporary American culture. When they
depict family lives, you almost always see one-husband/one-wife
families, with the couple raising their own biological children, and
so on, and so on. (There are rare exceptions.) Considering that there
have been many real-world Earth-human cultures for which this isn't
true, this represents a very strong &quot;obtrusive coincidence&quot; that the
writers made use of for convenience's sake. When you found out that
Vulcan men take a single wife (rather than, say, practice polygamy),
were you anoyed because this was so unnecessarily close to &quot;human&quot;?

Then how in the world can you get upset when they decide to let a
black actor play a Vulcan? Do you really want to claim that that's
&quot;too much like humans&quot; to be acceptable to you?

It was ALREADY an &quot;obtrusive coincidence&quot; that the &quot;racial&quot; traits of
Vulcans played by white actors matched human Caucasians so closely.
Letting a black actor play a Vulcan doesn't really make this worse.
Human actor, plays alien character, carries with him some visually
human characteristics that might not be present in a cartoon or a
novel. That's been true of Star Trek (and many other shows besides)
from Day 1.

WITHIN THE SHOW, they never made a big deal out of Tuvok being black.
I don't think they ever even called him a &quot;black Vulcan.&quot; There was no
indication that Vulcan had racial politics that resembled modern-day
real-life Earth. If you wanted to think of the actor as &quot;a black actor
playing a green Vulcan&quot; - or for that matter if you wanted to think of
Leonard Nimoy as a &quot;Jewish actor playing a green Vulcan&quot; - you were
perfectly free to. I simply do not understand why - with all the
physical and cultural similarities between humans and Vulcans, may of
which were simply &quot;artisitic license,&quot; and not required by the science-
fiction framework of the show (or even, in some cases, going against
that framework) - the introduction of one more (a black actor playing
a Vulcan, suggesting that Vulcans have races much like humans, just as
Vulcans have gender-specific hair customs much like humans) would
bother you, or anyone, in the least. Much less &quot;outrage&quot; you.
